ith profound consequences for labour regulation and worker organising. Theoretically innovative and empirically rich, the book provides essential insights into debates about gender, work, and urban economies that are critical to understanding southern Africa’s post-colonial and post-apartheid history.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 8, Decent work and economic growth  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHousehold employeesxSocial aspectszAfrica, Southern. 0aWomen household employeeszAfrica, SouthernxHistory. 0aWomen household employees, BlackzAfrica, SouthernxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Africa / South / General.2bisacsh  aChild workers.  aChildcare.  aDecent work and economic growth.  aDomestic labour.  aDomestic service.  aGender.  aLusaka.  aSouthern Africa.  aUrban.  aWomen.  aZambia.1 aSacha, Hepburn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616204540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526162045423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526162045/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles